        <page n="01" image="va.au.rv.1863.03.06">
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Bold Speech</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt>"Mr. Burr reiterated that Mr. Lincoln was a greater traitor than Jeff
                    Davis, and if his abolition policy was permitted to go on, he (Mr. B),
                    maintained that Jefferson Davis was fighting for liberties in the North, as well
                    as those of his fellow citizens in the South."</excerpt>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>C. C. Burr, at a speech at the Philadelphia Democratic Club, asserted that
                    the United States had no rights except state's rights and that the current
                    abolition policy was a disgrace.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Northwestern Virginia</head>
                <origin>Rockingham Register</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt>"Pierpont's bogus government is getting into bad odor, and is openly and
                    severely denounced by leading influential men, who have heretofore not
                    co-operated with the South."</excerpt>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Describes a meeting held at the courthouse in Wheeling of persons opposed
                    to establishing a new state and recounts the response to this meeting as
                    published in a pro-new state newspaper, the Intelligencer.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>For the Vindicator</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer>M. G. Harman</trailer>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Harman</ln>
                        <fn>M. G.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Hanger</ln>
                        <fn>E. V.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Miss</pf>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Harman expresses thanks to the Waynesboro Soldier's Aid Society for a
                    barrel of socks and shirts for the regiment.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>5</column>
                <head>To Our Farmers--Plant Corn</head>
                <origin>R. Examiner</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt>"Should our planters, labouring under the belief that a state of peace will
                    ensure before the maturing of the next crop, and that belief turn out to be a
                    failure, plant large crops of cotton, to the exclusion of grain, the most
                    disastrous results will, in our opinion, be felt by our government."</excerpt>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Encourages farmers to plant corn and other foodstuffs in order to feed the
                    armies. The Examiner argues that farmers can show their patriotism by planting
                    food instead of planting cotton for profit.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head/>
                <origin>Lynchburg Virginian</origin>
                <commentary>The Lynchburg "Virginian" well remarks.</commentary>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Encourages farmers to grow corn and other food stuffs and not be lured into
                    growing tobacco.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>From the Spectator</head>
                <origin>Spectator</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Harman</ln>
                        <fn>William H.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>This letter from "a refugee from Clark County" calls for the election of
                    William L. Goggin of Bedford as governor, Alex. R. Boteler of Jefferson as
                    lieutenant governor, and William H. Harman of Augusta for attorney general.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head/>
                <origin>New York Times</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Seeks to confirm rumors that the 133d regiment of New York Volunteers,
                    under the command of General Banks, has had trouble after the introduction of
                    African-American troops. Officers have resigned or refused to recognize the
                    troops.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head/>
                <origin>Mississippian</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Quotes a man from Mississippi who says that more than one thousand slaves
                    carried away by Northern troops have returned voluntarily to their owners,
                    citing the poor conditions and bad treatment.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <pageNote>The top third of column five is missing. This page also carries excerpts of
                other war news and a report from the state legislature.</pageNote>
